{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## What\nAdopt the B1 batch primitive (`_store.batch_stage_and_commit`, ticket 890d-4733-1c88-4976 —\n**hard prerequisite; this ticket `depends_on` B1**) on the NDJSON importer's independent\npasses so a bulk import commits far fewer commits than one-per-event.\n\n## Why\n`src/rebar/_io/import_ndjson.py` already has idempotency-by-`source_id` and deferred-push,\nbut each pass funnels through a per-event commit. Every write in the importer — CREATE\n(`composer.create_core`), parent/edit (`composer.edit_core`), comments and file-impact/\nverify (`_commands/leaf.py`), links (`graph._links.add_dependency`) — ultimately calls the\nONE sink `src/rebar/_commands/_seam.py::append_event`, which composes the event and commits\nit via `event_append.write_and_push`. That single sink is where the commit happens.\n\n## Deferred-commit sink (mechanism — a contextvar at ONE boundary, NOT kwarg-threading)\nIntroduce the compose/commit split at the SINGLE `_seam.append_event` boundary via a\nmodule-level `contextvars.ContextVar` `_batch_sink` (default `None`):\n- **`_batch_sink is None` (default):** `append_event` composes AND commits per-event exactly\n  as today. Every existing caller — interactive and library — is unchanged, with NO kwarg\n  threaded through `create_core`/`edit_core`/`leaf.*`/`_lib_writes`/`_lib_gates`. This is why\n  the edit surface is tiny and guardrail-1 (interactive writes stay one-commit-per-event) is\n  structurally guaranteed: nothing sets the contextvar outside the importer.\n- **`_batch_sink` set to a buffer (a `list[tuple[str, dict]]`):** `append_event` still lets\n  the caller's state-reading guards run (they execute BEFORE it) and still composes the\n  canonical event, but APPENDS the composed `(ticket_id, event_dict)` to the buffer instead\n  of committing. The importer owns the buffer, sets the contextvar around one pass, then\n  flushes via `batch_stage_and_commit` and resets the contextvar.\n\n## Scope (edit surface)\n- `src/rebar/_commands/_seam.py` — add the `_batch_sink` contextvar + a small helper\n  (`batch_sink(buffer)` contextmanager) and the \"append to sink vs commit\" branch in\n  `append_event`. This is the ONLY write-path source file changed.\n- `src/rebar/_io/import_ndjson.py` — for the independent, append-only passes **Pass 1\n  (CREATE), Pass 2a (parents), Pass 2c (file-impact/verify-commands), Pass 2d (comments)**,\n  wrap each pass in `batch_sink(buf)` and flush `buf` through `batch_stage_and_commit` in\n  chunks (default 256, hard-coded — no new config key). Passes run sequentially and each\n  pass's buffer is flushed (committed) before the next, so a later pass reads the prior\n  pass's committed state.\n- **Pass 2b (links) and Pass 2e (statuses) stay per-event (do NOT set the contextvar):**\n  2b because `add_dependency` does read-after-write within the pass (it emits TWO\n  `_write_link_event` calls for a reciprocal `relates_to` and calls `_is_active_link`, an\n  idempotency check that READS committed link state — buffering would make a later link in\n  the chunk unable to observe an earlier one, a TOCTOU); 2e because it is STATEFUL\n  (children-before-parents, `cascade=False`).\n\n## Commit-count math\nPer-pass flush -> total NEW commits = `sum_over_batched_passes(ceil(pass_events/256))` +\n(per-event commits from Pass 2b links and Pass 2e statuses). For a synthetic import of N=3000 tickets where each ticket has 1 CREATE + 1 comment and\n**NO parents, file-impact, verify-commands, links, or status transitions** (so Pass 1 and\nPass 2d each carry 3000 events and Passes 2a/2b/2c/2e carry zero), that is\n`ceil(3000/256) + ceil(3000/256) = 12 + 12 = 24` batch commits vs ~6000 per-event (>=10x\nfewer). The benchmark asserts the DELTA (commits after − before; baseline `init_repo`\ncommits excluded). A synthetic file that also exercises parents/file-impact adds\n`ceil(pass_2a/256) + ceil(pass_2c/256)` more batch commits.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `_batch_sink` contextvar + `batch_sink()` contextmanager in `src/rebar/_commands/_seam.py`; `append_event` appends the composed `(ticket_id, event_dict)` to the active sink and skips the commit when a sink is set, else commits per-event exactly as today (default path byte-for-byte unchanged)\n- [ ] Guardrail 1 preserved: only the importer ever sets the contextvar; interactive writes (`create`/`edit`/`transition`/`claim`/`link`/`comment`) still commit one-event-per-commit (a unit test asserts a normal `create`/`comment` still makes one commit each)\n- [ ] Importer Passes 1, 2a, 2c, 2d run under `batch_sink(buf)` and flush via `batch_stage_and_commit` in 256-event chunks; Pass 2b (links) and Pass 2e (statuses) remain per-event\n- [ ] Equivalence PROVEN by a pytest that imports the same NDJSON into two trackers (per-event vs batched) and asserts equal replayed state via a concrete normalizer: for each ticket id, load `rebar.show(tid)` (the reducer's replayed dict) from both stores, delete the volatile keys (`created_at`, `updated_at`, `env_id`, and every event/comment `uuid`+`timestamp`), and assert the two normalized dicts are equal for every ticket (a raw `git ls-tree` diff is NOT valid because event filenames embed per-run `uuid`/`timestamp`). Concretely: `assert _normalize(show_all(t_per_event)) == _normalize(show_all(t_batched))` where `_normalize` strips those keys\n- [ ] Benchmark: a synthetic N=3000 import where each ticket has only 1 CREATE + 1 comment (no parents/file-impact/verify/links/statuses, so only Pass 1 and Pass 2d carry events) makes the commit-count delta = `2*ceil(3000/256)` (=24), >=10x fewer than the ~6000 per-event commits\n- [ ] Idempotent re-import (source_id re-scan) still skips already-imported events (no duplicate events, no extra commits)\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && python -m pytest tests/ -k import -q` all green"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783655346772774001,"uuid":"d25cd8b8-5167-4103-8388-a3debdab82c7"}